Russian President Vladimir Putin signed a law introducing administrative responsibility for violations of the payment terms and conditions for goods (works, services) when purchasing for state and municipal needs.
This law is designed to solve the very acute problem of non-fulfilment of obligations by customers when carrying out state and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation where entrepreneurs could not get paid for their government and municipal contracts was widespread.
At the same time, the Russian president instructed the Prosecutor General's Office to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with unscrupulous customers who signed contracts without backing, tried to evade their payment obligations and included illegal terms in the contracts.
The problem was systemic throughout the country.
Since 2015, in the interests of protecting the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment on public orders, the prosecutor's office has submitted 9,7 thousand submissions, 4,5 thousand officials have been brought to disciplinary responsibility, 533 to administrative responsibility, 75 materials have been submitted to the investigative bodies for the organization of procedural checks, 46 of them have been prosecuted.
As a result, more than 66 billion rubles of debts were paid off.
And these huge sums were not accumulated by the failure to pay multibillion-dollar contracts.
The fabulous debts were caused by the numerous, systematic delays in paying the entrepreneurs for services of much more modest amounts.
That's a typical case.
A small company's head won a million-ruble competition for social transportation services.
The man has invested all his working capital, has fully fulfilled his obligations, but has not received the money in time.
The result is a growing financial debt of salaries, taxes, loans, which would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not sought help from the prosecutor's office.
Now, in some regions, the problem has been reduced to a minimum.
Nevertheless, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts identified by the prosecutors of the Russian Federation's subjects amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt levels continue to reach critical levels, the prosecutor's office operates in a manual crisis management mode.
The Prosecutor General personally holds visiting meetings with local authorities to discuss all the violations and measures to remedy them immediately.
Such operational meetings have already been held in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg this year.
The implementation of the Federal Law No. 189-FZ "On introducing changes to the Code of the Russian Federation on administrative offences in respect of the establishment of administrative responsibility of the officials of the customer for violating the term and order of payment of goods (works, services) when carrying out purchases for the provision of state and municipal needs" which was signed by the President of Russia last week will improve the payment discipline of public customers.
The draft law was developed by the Russian Ministry of Economic Development on the initiative of the Prosecutor General's Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of the Russian Federation on administrative offenses with an article that provides a fine of from 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation by a responsible person of the customer of the term and order of payment of goods, works and services at state and municipal purchases.
If the official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offence, he is liable to disqualification for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the Russian Federation have already received instructions to ensure the application of these legislative novelties in practice.
