The poem you refer to was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty".
Miller's right about the facts, but as he said, it's not really about the story.
It is about the current sound of Lazarus's astonishing words, the only ones in which the state invites not just any immigrants, but the poorest: "Your tired, your poor, / your crowds, dreaming to breathe freely, / the unhappy waste of your abundant shores".
Never before has "unfortunate waste" been so visible on our screens.
Miller wasn't a literary scholar, he made it clear that Trump was not wanted in America.
This debate about the meaning of the statue is part of a larger political and cultural war: it's really a debate about the meaning of America.
