Blocking critics on Facebook: Don't run for public office if you're not prepared to listen to voter criticism
The founder of our country understood what a critical press was.
Americans loved George Washington, but that didn't stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic policy to his political principles.
The criticism, of course, annoyed him.
But he didn't shut up about his critics.
Because back in 1783, Washington said, "you can take away freedom of speech and we deaf and dumb will be led like sheep to the slaughter".
Now I'm going to go to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should try to be more like Washington.
Hogan's followers have blocked and deleted posts from at least 450 people who have expressed their views on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for that.
The governor's subordinates called the lawsuit a "simple" one, and the online commentary was written in the spirit of "well and what".
"It's just Facebook", many would say.
But that's important, too.
And that's especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He's a surprisingly popular Republican governor in a predominantly Democratic state.
He's second in the approval rating of the 50 governors in the country.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He has shown a firm hand in running the state and a commitment to his principles.
He also is adept at using Facebook as his primary means of communicating with his constituents and jokingly displays his bald head after chemotherapy on his page.
So blocking people who visit the governor's page - which is billed as an official public forum and run by taxpayer-funded administration employees - is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with The Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Ches defended the governor's actions, arguing that blocking comments was simply moderation.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers and haters doing evil on the Internet.
The Post spoke to some of the real people Hogan blocked.
And it's real people, not trolls, the teacher, the businessman, the pastor, who are addressing their elected leaders.
They all say their comments were respectful, meaningful, and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing to the fact that Hogan was a Catholic.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Ramana of Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
"I wrote a polite comment saying I was disappointed by his lack of reaction to hate crimes and other recent news", she wrote in the Post's comment section.
"I also don't like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say it's a so-called twist, instead of admitting that they're dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens".
What the governor's subordinates call a "concentrated spam attack", others would probably call an "active life position".
In the Facebook era, it's easy to edit your image simply by blocking critics or deleting negative comments.
It's a lot less dusty than it used to be, when it required sending people, collecting and burning newspapers with critical editorials, or arresting and silencing protesters.
But that's exactly what's happening now, only in numbers.
Hogan is not the first official to be criticized for not listening to Facebook and other social media.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who were banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first, pivotal decisions on this issue was made this week in Virginia.
According to U.S. District Judge James K. Casheris of Alexandria, the chairman of the Laudon County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment by banning a voter from her Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bavin was sued by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington's day, the era of affordable mail was about as revolutionary as the Internet is today.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and anonymous letters greatly eroded his reputation.
And even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People using the aliases "Uricola", "Valerius", "Belizarus", and "Porcius" wrote letters to the newspapers mocking Washington's decision.
According to historical documents compiled by the online project The George Washington Papers, his office was flooded with petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Amity, Commerce and Navigation.
But he didn't try to shut them up.
Freedom of speech, dissent and expression is at the very core of our state.
And true leadership is about accepting that.
