Poverty and Death in the Golden Land of Indonesia
When he cooks dinner, Bardina Degay doesn't use a stove.
She's not even used to it.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Paniay County in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, a housewife usually just puts a sweet potato, here called nota, right in the fireplace.
After half an hour, the charred club is pulled out and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degeie sits on the earthen floor  she has no furniture  and it is here that she does her housework, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
A bucket is used as a toilet in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband's four wives, and so she was not assigned to work in the fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men in this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
"Nobody dares to walk around the village after five in the evening", she says.
It's a rare opportunity to look at everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a questionable referendum, when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote by publicly raising their hands in front of occupying troops.
The existing movement for independence from the Netherlands quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which maintains tight control over the region, not allowing foreign journalists and human rights activists.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupying the eastern part of the island.
Enoratali is as remote as it is abandoned; the journey here involves a one-and-a-half-hour flight from Jayapura, the administrative center of the province, to Nabir, and then a five-hour ride in a rented car.
There's no public transport here.
The city of about 19,000 people consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences; the roofs are of corrugated steel and painted with rust in various reddish tones.
Few Indonesians, let alone journalists, and almost no foreigners have been here.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Papuans worshipped a god named Uga Tameye.
There were other changes.
"We were not used to wearing these clothes", says Degei, pointing to her bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
We used to wear only leaves.
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of the population living below the poverty line, and infant mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
But it's also the land of Indonesian gold.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just sixty miles from Paniay, a mountainous province about the size of New Jersey with 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined gold and copper here for about $3.1 billion.
In addition, Papua boasts forest reserves worth an estimated $78 billion.
This wealth, however, brings one disaster for the Papuans, ensuring that Indonesia's powerful military maintains its suffocating presence.
According to a 2005 New York Times investigation, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly $20 million, including up to $150,000 per officer.
The demands for greater autonomy by the Papuans threaten the existence of this golden vein and are being ruthlessly suppressed.
Human rights activists claim that since 1969, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by Indonesian military forces, and thousands more have been raped, tortured, and imprisoned.
The Asian Commission on Human Rights has stated that the mass killings in the highlands of Papua in the 1970s can be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
"We will lose everything", a report published in 2016 by the Diocese of Brisbane, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as executions without trial, torture - particularly frequent, as claimed in another report, rape and electrocution - and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's hard to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week", says Andreas Harsono, a researcher in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The gaiki were delayed as Papua's resources attracted an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The province's 3.5 million population is 83% Christian, but demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese stalls, called warung, sell fried chicken and a mix of vegetables, called gadō-gadō, served with peanut sauce.
The locals are trying to keep up with the competition.
"Migrants have started selling chicken and vegetables at a traditional marketplace that is cheaper than the indigenous people of Papua", explains Abet Yow, a 24-year-old native of Paniay who moved to Jayapura, the administrative center of the province, for work.
Because of this, the indigenous people of Papua have lost their market.
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Djokovic, vowed to address inequality and human rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including Paniay.
But in Papua, almost nothing has changed, and the locals feel loyal.
"Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Djokovic, expecting him to fulfill our hopes of restoring justice", says Yow.
In fact, just two months after his October inauguration, Djokovic Paniai suffered a tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were out singing Christmas carols by a bonfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on motorcycles broke out of the darkness.
The frightened children told them they should turn on the lights.
According to local pastor Javed Tebai, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and returned with four soldiers after a while.
Victims and witnesses said soldiers who were drunk chased the children and beat them with rifle butts.
Then one of the soldiers shot a group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Julianus Aimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to the nearby government election commission building, and the next day the situation escalated.
About a thousand Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought their ritual hunting bows and performed the waita, a dance of the Mye Pago tribe of Papua, running in circles and imitating the song of birds.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and military base.
When the situation escalated, soldiers were told over internal radio: "If the mob resists more than three times, shoot them", according to an official document seen by TIME magazine correspondents but not published by local media.
Jeremiah Kayame, 56, the head of the Kego Koto district in Enarotali, sensed the danger and called for calm, asking the crowd to disperse to their homes.
No one wanted to listen to him.
"When I turned around, I was hit by a bullet in my left wrist", he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who fired the shot, but says the bullet came from the side of the soldiers' lines.
"There was a crowd, there was a lot of gunfire", he adds.
Local resident Alfie Yoava was shot three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
"I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him", Johannes, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name, told TIME magazine gloomily.
I saw him dead... I kissed him.
General Yotje Mende, the chief inspector of the Papua police, told reporters that his officers were only "protecting" their base because it was under attack.
"We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us", said Papua Police Commissioner Pujo Sulistio in 2015.
It's a matter of life and death.
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
News of the murders did not reach Jakarta until the next day.
Three weeks later, Djokovic delivered a passionate speech in Jayapura, expressing his condolences to the families of the victims and vowing to address the issue of historical abuse of power in Papua.
"I want this situation to be resolved immediately so that it never happens again in the future", he said.
In October 2016, Minister of Security Viranto said he would establish a non-judicial organization to end historic human rights abuses.
But the excuses almost immediately.
Most of the violations happened a long time ago.
Some of them were in the '90s or early '00s.
The fact is that we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be followed", he said.
Viranto then retracted his words, speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he had no plans to set up an organization to handle complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, "It's going to be decided by the court".
Viranto, who was accused by the United Nations of "crimes against humanity" in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people during the 1999 East Timorese independence vote, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been settled, including the incident in Paniay.
The families of the victims in Paniay greeted such statements with gloomy distrust.
"I was interrogated four times in the last three years, but nothing changed", says Johannes.
I'm tired of it.
He says he's still living in fear years later.
