But when the noose was thrown around Roger's neck, almost everyone in the audience actually held their breath.
Since 2005, activists have been returning to the Morse Ford Bridge to recreate the night in 1946 when the Doll Clan lynched two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and May Murray Dorsey.
No one's ever been convicted of these murders.
"It's amazing that no one has been arrested over the years - even though we see them around us; even though we know who they are", says Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the production.
"It's a stain on our history and a stone on our souls".
Brooks, 71, is a former Georgia congressman who has spent his life fighting for human rights.
To him, the play is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to the people of Monroe that injustice has never been rectified.
"We want investigations, we want completions, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice", he says.
"We cannot move on to healing and reconciliation until we achieve justice".
A coroner covering the body of one of the victims of the lynching at Morse Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI materials obtained by NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and surrounding counties were suspected of involvement in the lynching.
But no one was ever charged.
Although the suspects have been out for decades, human rights activists say the city has always been well aware of the two interconnected motives of the lynchings: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court decision allowed black citizens to vote for the first time in the primaries that were to be held that summer.
Around the same time as the election, the FBI reported that black exploiter Roger Malcolm stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, in a fight, apparently over a woman.
Brooks says that, according to rumors circulating in the city, Hester had slept with Malcolm's wife Dorothy, and that the child she was about to have was not from her husband.
According to FBI reports, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a large white landowner, paid $600 in bail to free Malcolm from prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But as they drove from the prison and approached the Morse Ford Bridge, a mob of lynchers surrounded the car.
"It turns out that Harrison organized and ordered the murders", concludes one FBI report.
"It is also clear that there was collusion between state and city law enforcement, "who not only participated in the killings, "but also destroyed evidence and concealed the identities of witnesses".
Brooks calls it short.
"It was an attempt on the voting rights", he says.
"They were all killed to send a message to the black people in this town that if you register and vote, you will be the same".
For almost a decade, Cassandra Green has directed the annual performance of the lynching at the Morse Ford Bridge.
Her performance is visual, it captivates the viewer and it tells the story of a deep-seated racism that many would like to believe is no longer in America.
It's hard to look at, and it's harder to turn away, but Green thinks that's the point.
"We don't want to talk about lynch trials because they show us our own ugliness", she says.
"But I can't build a relationship with you if you don't listen to me or hear what I've been through".
This year's rehearsal began in June, and on the first day, nearly 30 actors - a dozen white, the rest black - gathered in the room to listen to a refined review of the play over the years.
Wade Marbo was the co-director with Green.
He's been a key member of the clan for a few years, but he says the role has never been easier.
"I feel like I'm dirty because that's not the person I am", says Marbo.
"But I think it's really important to remember this story, because we don't want to go back to that time".
In the room, actors Darius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, reprise their roles.
The play begins with Malcolm, furious that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, screaming and pushing him.
"I said, nigga, get out of my house!"
Rascon shouts back.
The blow is coming.
And at the same moment, everyone (at least all the black actors) is getting a little bit of a scratch.
Green is the loudest laughing person.
"What is it?" Asks Ascona.
He's worried and embarrassed.
Am I playing too much?
"No", Green says through laughter.
"I just don't think white people used to say 'nigga' back then".
"Yeah, yeah", one of the black performers laughs.
"You have to get through the solid 'r.'"
And so the energy in the room changes: discomfort is replaced by a sense of companionship.
Everyone has to do the right thing, not just for the play, but for the memory of the four people who were killed.
The scene starts again.
This time, when Rascona says the word with the letter "n", it's clear and sharp.
No one is laughing.
The play ends violently and quickly.
Screams, shots, and then silence.
A woman in a mourning black dress stands over the bodies of the actors and sings the sad song "Strange Fruit" by Billy Holiday.
Her voice is interrupted by a word.
A hundred yards away, half a hundred spectators wipe their tears and sweat from their eyes.
There's almost equal numbers of black and white in the audience.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York, to see the show; many live right next door.
They all endured the heavy spirit of Georgia for nearly eight hours while Brooks led them on a pilgrimage to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Until then, the murders were just history, but now that they're standing in the same place where the people were lynched, it seems like their ghosts are just floating in the air.
When the last note of the song is silenced, Green invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
The children lean against their heads, touch the paint that represents blood and still bodies, and whisper something to each other.
"They're not really dead", murmurs one little boy, as if to remind himself.
A few minutes later, Green is thanking the audience, and suddenly it's over.
Actors throw the ropes off their necks and wipe away the tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbo, the man in the suit who played the head puppet master.
Nick Rascona hugs the other two actors and suddenly, crying, falls into their arms: the emotional load of the play finally falls on him.
"It's all right", whispers one of the women.
"We know you have a good heart.
You had your reasons".
Later, the audience sits down to dinner with the actors.
At one table, a white couple from Atlanta are discussing a play with a black couple they've just met.
Denise Daplinsky is struggling to find the words to describe how she feels after the performance.
"It's hard to hear these horrible, horrible words and actions... from people who look like you and who do it because they look like you", she says.
"After that, I think lynchings still happen", she adds, "only now it's called the police shooting".
In another corner of the room, the attention was drawn to Tyrone Brooks, who, over dinner, recalls his work as a human rights activist.
He says he's already started planning next year's show.
"The play inspires us because it not only describes the horror of what we have experienced but also teaches us", he says.
"Because if you don't learn from this, it could happen again.
Those who do not learn their history, who do not know their history, are doomed to repeat it".
