New results of tests to assess the age of asylum seekers in Sweden
The latest results of the tests of asylum seekers in Sweden, who were subjected to a new medical age assessment method, show that more than 80 percent of those tested were assessed as being over 18 years old, but not everyone trusts the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish National Agency for Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) started testing earlier this year.
They were designed to make the age assessment in the asylum process more accurate after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the true age of some refugees who claimed to be minors.
At the moment, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests for the period between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) of those tested were rated as 18 years of age or older, and in 25 other cases, the forensic medicine agency estimated that the test subject was "likely to be 18 years of age or older".
In 432 cases, the verdict was that the person was "probably less than 18".
Tests are only done when the person's age is in doubt.
Johan Göransson from the forensic medicine agency said the results were consistent with the results from the previous months.
"We don't see much difference from the statistics of the previous months, the numbers are quite consistent", he told the portal The Local.
The high proportion of cases where people were assessed as over 18 does not necessarily indicate that asylum seekers lied about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and reported that 442 cases were "likely to be 18 years or older".
However, after reviewing 581 published results, the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet found that in 243 cases the person openly stated that 18 of them were coming to fruition this year.
The method of medical age assessment, which consists of taking an x-ray of wisdom teeth and a CT scan of the knee joints and giving them to dentists and radiologists for analysis, has also drawn criticism from some authorities.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Carolina Institute of Technology, whose work involves assessing people's biological maturity to determine whether they have gone through puberty earlier or later than usual.
I had reasons to think about it, and I don't think we should use the measurement methods that we use now.
Biological age is thus determined very inaccurate.
If we can't identify it with certainty, we shouldn't pretend we can", he told Metro.
However, Göranssen of the Forensic Medicine Agency spoke in favour of the accuracy of the tests: In general, the risk of mistaking a child for an adult is low.
The greatest risk we face is when a person is about to turn 18, in which case it's about 10 percent.
