The President will determine the place and the procedure for swearing the oath .
Where and how new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the president - such amendments to the second reading of the relevant law were developed by the State Duma Committee on Legislation and State Construction.
A week ago, the lawmakers were planning to directly define the oath-taking procedure in the law.
Children under 18 years old, as well as those who are incapable of working, will be exempt from taking the oath, according to the revised text of amendments to the draft law "On citizenship of the Russian Federation" (at the disposal of "Izvestie"), which the committee will consider on July 11 before the second reading at its meeting.
The idea of introducing the oath of citizenship instead of formal signing of documents was supported by President Vladimir Putin on June 6 during a meeting with the speaker of the State Duma, Vyacheslav Volodin.
The lawmakers formulated this idea as an amendment to the second reading of the bill, which provides for the abolition of the decision to grant citizenship to those who were subsequently convicted of a number of terrorist or extremist crimes: for example, for public calls for terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet (part 2 of article 205.2 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation), as well as for the theft of an aircraft, a train or a water transport, but only if this act is connected with terrorism (part 4 of article 211 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation).
According to the bill, the logic was this: when a person signs a citizenship document, he promises to abide by Russian law - and by taking the path of extremism, he violates that promise.
The draft law was introduced in April by the leaders of the Duma factions Vladimir Vasilyev ("United Russia"), Gennady Zyuganov (KPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergey Mironov ("Justice Russia") and the speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
On May 19, the deputies adopted it in the first reading.
Last week, the State Department's Committee on Housing and Legislation approved the bill for a second reading, but now it's been reworked.
Now it says that the order of swearing-in will be set by the president of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, the parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law "On citizenship of the Russian Federation", indicating that the ceremony should take place in a solemn setting before the state emblem and flag of Russia in the presence of the representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, the text of the bill did not make it clear where such an event should take place - the list of places where the coat of arms of the Russian Federation can be placed is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include courts, the cabinets of heads of state authorities, municipal entities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive authorities, etc.
It could have been the ZAP.
Those who wish to become Russian citizens will take the oath after the officials check their documents.
But a Russian passport will only be issued after the oath, according to the revised text.
A week ago, the draft said that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text says that the Russian will be sworn in at 18, not 14.
The rule that incapacitated or disabled persons, as well as those unable to pronounce, read or sign the text of the oath, would be exempt from taking the oath was retained.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt "other persons" from this procedure,
The updated bill also stipulates a special procedure for accepting Ukrainian residents who are native speakers of Russian as Russian citizens.
They will have to formally renounce their Ukrainian citizenship by submitting a request to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the application will need to be sent to Russian officials.
The renunciation of "foreign" citizenship, as now, will not be required if it is provided for by an international treaty or if it is impossible "for reasons beyond the individual's control".
The amendment was proposed by a group of deputies, among whom were the first vice-speaker of the State Duma Ivan Melnikov (KPRF), Natalia Poklonskaya, Pavel Kresheninikov and Airat Farakhov (all - "United Russia").
I think many of you know that getting a certificate from Ukraine is not real, it's just impossible.
Accordingly, many people are waiting for their fate to be decided on the basis of Russian citizenship, - explained the head of the Duma Committee on State Construction and Legislation, Pavel Kresheninnikov (ER).
In addition, the text clarified that the restrictions on foreigners' employment in certain positions would not apply to those who had written a waiver of "another" citizenship and had submitted their previous passport to the Russian Interior Ministry, but "for reasons not dependent on it" had not ceased to be considered a citizen of another country.
Now foreigners are forbidden to hold positions in municipal services, to be employed in facilities and organizations whose activities are connected with ensuring the security of Russia.
A person with dual citizenship or a residence permit from another country cannot become a state Duma member or a member of the Federation Council.
The law is scheduled to enter into force on 1 September 2017, with the necessary legislative acts ready by then.
Nostalgia becomes a niche in Hot American Summer and Detective Comedy.
The current iteration of the story nostalgically recalls both the glory days of the characters in the '80s; the grunge era in the '90s (around the time when the great masters David Wayne and Michael Showalter made the sketch comedy The State for MTV); and the year 2001 itself, before its stars like Elizabeth Banks, Paul Emil and Paul Rudd moved on to bigger things.
As a cultural fact, it is both the elevation and the embodiment of our age with its constant reminders from Facebook.
But as a franchise, it seems anachronistic.
"First Day of Camp" was surprisingly good, and not just because of the absurd humor (including the original story about a talking vegetable bank voiced by H. John Benjamin).
The result is double the main joke: middle-aged actors play sexually-obsessed children who have just reached adulthood; this makes the impossibility of returning to the main joke part of the joke.
Ten Years Later, where adults played adults, has less deep emotional roots, and its parody is more disorderly and incorporates riffs from 90s stalker films like Hands That Rocked the Cradle.
In one episode, the character gets an Apple Powerbook, a four-wheeled roller skater, and "a bunch of other stuff from 1991".
A lot of the plot moves are the same.
Good-natured Coop, now a writer, still hasn't gotten a reciprocation from Kathy.
Victor (Ken Marino) is still a virgin.
And then there's the crazy and vile conspiracy involving Ronald Reagan (aka Showalter), which is now being instigated by George H.W. Bush (a tried-and-true parody of Michael Ian Blake).
As always, the best part of a franchise is the withdrawal.
It's especially fun to see the ever-young Rudd singing Matt Dillon's "Lonesome People" song, whose character, the former big man Andy, now looks old-fashioned.
The franchise could have been a success in the spirit of the recurring series "Seven Up", until it reached what I think would be its logical conclusion: "Hot American Summer: Twenty Years Later", where the entire company would have gone to the cinema for the premiere of "Hot American Summer" in the final scene.
"Comrade Detective" in the Amazon addresses another type of nostalgia: Cold War memories from "Americans", "Blood Blower", or even "Blink" with its images of the struggle of East and West.
This comedy, created by Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaka with director Riz Thomas, depicts a TV movie: a Romanian police drama from the 1980s about two police officers in Bucharest fighting for truth, atheism and the Marxist-Leninist path.
The main roles - the life-seeing Gregor and the idealist Josef - are performed by Florin Piersik the younger and Cornelius Ulich, and their dialogues in English are voiced by Channing Tatum (the same executive producer) and Joseph Gordon-Levitt.
That's a brilliant idea.
But it's just an idea.
There are a few visual jokes (police spending time watching a chess match, as Americans might watch football).
The team of famous voices behind the scenes - including Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershal Ali and Chloe Sevigny - makes it interesting to play "guess the voice".
But Comrade Detective is so attached to the truth of the awkward propaganda drama -- there's even a killer in the Ronald Reagan mask -- that it often looks like it.
Six long episodes are long, and funny is not very often.
If it had been shorter, Comrade Detective could have handled its agitprop satire better; for example, every time Gregor and Joseph come to the American Embassy, there are two fat men sitting in the lobby, devouring a bunch of hamburgers.
To the imaginary communist viewer, this image tells us that Western culture is capable of making a food trap out of anything.
The Romanian filmmakers are not so wrong: we do this even with our own recent history, and with theirs as well.
