In its quarterly inflation report, the bank limited its forecasts to a rise of 1.7% percent in 2017 and 1.6% in 2018 and warned that pressure on household incomes would continue, while inflation was still expected to rise to around 3% in the fall.
However, the bank warned that rate hikes in the next few years would be necessary to control Brexit-induced inflation, and said it was likely that borrowing costs would have to be raised more than expected in financial markets.
