State health service will prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people
Starting in September, patients will have access to the "revolutionary" HIV prevention drug after a high court battle over funding for the drug from the National Health Service.
England's National Health Service announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), a pill taken before sex that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in those at risk, on average, by 86 percent, will now be provided by the health service for an initial three-year trial period of approximately 10,000 people.
She agreed to fund the trial after an appeals court upheld a High Court ruling last year that the National Health Service had the ability to pay for the PRE despite her claims that it should be funded by local authorities.
The move, announced on Thursday, was called a "major innovation" by Simon Stevens, president of England's National Health Service, and the National AIDS Administration (NAT) called it a "turning point".
Before the programme is fully rolled out across England by April 2018, venereal dispensaries in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to register people, with even more dispensaries joining the programme in October.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PREP)  is a course of HIV medications taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PREP significantly reduces the risk of HIV infection among people at risk.
When you take PrEP before sex, there's enough of certain drugs in your body to prevent you from getting HIV.
These medications can be taken daily or no later than two hours before sex.
Patients eligible for the drug include gay and bisexual men, transgender people, and people whose partners are HIV-positive and are not receiving successful treatment.
Dispensaries will select suitable participants who have agreed to participate in the study, including men, women, transgender people and those whose partners are not known to have been cured of HIV by antiretroviral therapy.
People living and registered with a general practitioner in England may also apply for potential participation at the nearest participating venereology clinic.
The programme will cost £10 million, and the NHS in England has signed a contract to supply the drug this week following an international tender.
The study is designed to evaluate all the potential of PREP by collecting clinical data on the target audience, its absorption and its widespread use.
This important innovation should complement and reinforce the large-scale and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
This is another milestone in more than three decades of success in the fight against one of the greatest health threats facing humanity.
Deborah Gold, president of NAT (National AIDS Control Office), said: "This is a watershed moment in the fight against HIV.
PR, if properly targeted at people in need and at risk, has the potential to change the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, people at risk for HIV, thanks to this study, funded by the National Health Service in England, will have access to a new, innovative tool that they can control themselves without having to discuss it with their partner, and that will improve many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this news.
Jan Green, president of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: "The first priority now is to make sure that the trial is rapidly rolled out nationwide, and that no one at risk for HIV is left behind.
Now that we have the experimental PrEP drug, we're moving on to protecting the more than 10,000 people at risk for HIV.
Shadow Public Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: "We are very pleased with the start of the PREP trial, which has been delayed by months of delays and delays from the government".
The data demonstrates how revolutionary this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and stopping the transmission of this fatal infection.
This test will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PREP.
It is now important that the trial be rolled out nationwide as soon as possible to protect those at risk for HIV and to take us one step closer to stopping the spread of HIV in society.
