Judges are being offered protection from the chairmen .
The Presidential Council on Human Rights (PCHR) on the instructions of Vladimir Putin developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judicial branch of government.
The ECHR proposes to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts and to introduce their electability.
For the courts of appeal and cassation instances, the ECHR wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court must also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential mandate.
The ECHR has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of the Russian justice system.
The SPH carried out this work on the instructions of Vladimir Putin dated January 3, 2017, which the president gave after meeting with the members of the council.
At the meeting with the members of the council on 8 December 2016, some cases of arbitrary judgments, as well as the problems of public control in places of detention of citizens were discussed (see "Ъ" of 9 December).
The ECHR's work resulted in 25 proposals, which addressed issues of ensuring the independence of judges and identifying judicial errors, as well as financing courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin's human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts to increase the independence of the other judges.
If the candidate for the position of judge has successfully passed the competition and has received the support of the judicial community, then the chairman of the court, in the opinion of the ECJ, should nominate him for appointment, without having the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed to deprive the chairman of the right to divide cases between judges.
Experts suggest that a specially written computer program may be able to do this.
The Supreme Court also held that the chairman is not entitled to "predetermine the results of the judge's qualification, initiate his disciplinary action, or make decisions on additional material payments".
The presidential council believes it is necessary to move to "electing the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves" and "to give them their powers for a relatively short period with mandatory rotation".
Now all the judges (from the republican to the district) are appointed for six years by the president on the proposal of the chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
To protect judges from the pressure of regional administrations, the ECHR proposes to reorganise appeals and cassation in courts of general jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Special Special Court says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation instances not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the subjects of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts".
Experts are guided by the practice of arbitration courts.
They have "court districts" that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but which guarantee greater independence from regional officials, who have difficulty using the "telephone law".
The ECHR proposes to strengthen the world's judges with people's judges to consider some "categories of civil and administrative cases".
For example, deprivation of parental rights, reinstatement at work, protection of honour and dignity, deprivation of driving licence, etc.
"These are just our proposals", explained to "Ъ" the member of the Supreme Court, retired judge of the Constitutional Court Tamara Morshakov.
She also recalled that the President's instruction did not only apply to the Supreme Court, but also to the Supreme Court (SJ), which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
The time for the implementation of the order is still available to the Armed Forces (among the co-executives - the Prosecutor General's Office and the Russian Commissioner for Human Rights).
Vyacheslav Lebedev, the chairman of the Supreme Court, has until September 1 to report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is being ensured in the Russian Federation.
Living high: the half-floor and the ingenious design techniques have turned this little apartment in Earls Court into a spacious home.
Joan Lee, a former banker with a passion for real estate, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the ground floor of a nice Queen Anne style house, and the fact that Joan hasn't packed her things and moved again is a good sign of the new design.
"I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge on a much larger plot", Joan recalls.
I was looking for something comparable for my money.
They showed me this apartment in Earls Court, and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered the price the same day.
Since the first inspection, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
Originally it was a one-bedroom apartment with a complex layout - to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen - and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a basement to maximize the use of the generous height of the ceilings.
I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
"That was my demand", she says.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi from Notting Hill-based architectural design studio Duck & Shed to use the 12.5 foot ceilings and create a home that would not only be a successful project but also be suitable for Joan to live in.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate the two rooms one above the other, so the architectural task was to create a half-floor where one could stand tall.
Erfan had to think creatively to handle the brief.
"Working with steel structures is very difficult", he explains.
We needed to place the rooms so that they were on top of each other and didn't have to bend.
The idea was not to build a simple platform, but to bend the structures so that they were at the right height and allowed the use of the rooms above and below.
This solution allowed Erfan to arrange two full-sized rooms one above the other in the allocated space  and many other interesting things.
From the ground floor, through the copper windows of the Retrouvius, a view is available of the luxurious living room below.
The mirrored gold-finished furniture, silver accents and vintage lighting fixtures from Serge Muya set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding spectacle, space, and light.
The short corridor is framed with mirrors to make it look longer.
In the kitchen, the mirrored guard panel looks like a window to another room.
The mirror cabinets at the entrance are used to store all Joan's dishes.
To create a more luxurious feel, the beauty of the living room can be a wall around the kitchen when it's not being used.
There's nothing new about folding kitchens.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it's a sliding door, like a garage.
"Here engineering was involved", Erfan says of the steel-armored wooden-fiber shield door.
It's got a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily.
By using space and storage space wisely, Joan gained an additional 50 square feet [16 sq m], an additional bedroom, and improved layout.
"After all, floor space is what you're going to sell, that is, what your property is valued on", Erfan says.
Roughly speaking, a real estate agent will come in and do the calculations based on floor area.
Here they were able to increase the floor area by using high-quality materials that give the space a luxurious touch.
"Materials are things we touch, so they help us to create an emotional connection with the home", says Erfan.
Nobody falls in love with the wiring in the walls.
It's important, but it doesn't touch the strings of our hearts.
This is a testament to how, with good design and increased footprint, an apartment can go from being ordinary to being amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you may choose to stay.
