Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of the board of directors of the AFL club and, according to a 2015 biography of Eddie McGwire, a best friend of the TV star.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
Only Colin responded, texting, saying that since the case had not yet been heard in court, "I really have nothing much to say".
"I am very, very sorry that my brother Paul decided to sue me and to trample our family's name in court", he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in his deposition that he was trying to satisfy his brother's demands.
"Our father would not like to see Paul and I argue in court", he said, adding that he "is still hoping for a resolution".
On Friday, that hope seems to have dissipated.
"The court will soon rule on our case", Colin wrote.
The new Trump chief of staff is planning to restrict access to the president.
Others have tried to do so and have failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can really do it.
Then he'll be the first.
Politico reports that the new White House chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information to President Trump, including news reports from the media, in the hope of keeping the chief in a more calm state.
