How did that work?
Three months later, Kelly's trying to do the same thing.
He may turn out to be a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump still has an impulsive nature, and his aides are still fighting each other for influence.
These constant factors make Kelly's task very difficult.
Tyumen prosecutor 's office is fighting HIV dissident
The prosecutor's office challenged the decision of the Tyumen district court in Kaliningrad to terminate the criminal case against a local woman whose infant daughter died of HIV.
According to the investigation, the child died because the mother was HIV-dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court acquitted her of any responsibility for her reconciliation with the father.
The prosecution believes that the crime cannot go unpunished, so as not to set a precedent for other HIV dissidents.
The case against Tyumen resident was initiated under part 1 of article 109 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (causing death by negligence) in April - after her three-year-old daughter died of HIV infection 4B stage.
According to the prosecutor's office, the mother herself is HIV-positive.
"The woman did not treat herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that HIV infection does not exist", - explained in the prosecutor's office of the Tyumen region.
The criminal case was submitted to the Tyumen's Kalininsky district court, which on July 25 decided to terminate it.
The father of the girl who died filed a petition saying that he "forgave his wife, had no claims against her, she has compensated for the damage and apologized".
The prosecution disagreed with the court's decision and filed an appeal, demanding that the decision to terminate the case be reversed and sent for a new hearing.
The girl is dead, and the damage done by the crime is impossible to undo.
The HIV-infected mother, despite the recommendations of doctors, refused to examine the baby and treat her for a dangerous infection", the press service of the prosecutor's office reported.
The supervisory authority believes she should be punished or other HIV dissidents will follow her example.
According to the Tyumen AIDS Center, about 12 children with HIV in the Tyumen region are not receiving medical care because their parents refuse.
"The situation has improved - over the year of the special group's work, half of the parents who had categorically refused to treat their children for HIV changed their minds - they allowed the diagnosis to be made, they began taking medicines", said the spokeswoman for the AIDS Center, Elena Loseva.
According to her, it is impossible to influence parents by law, and as a result not all HIV-infected children are detected - mothers do not allow them to be examined, hide, run away with their children from hospitals.
What Danger Is in HIV Dissidents
At the end of last year, St. Petersburg sociologists presented the results of Russia's first study of the so-called HIV-dissident movement.
HIV dissidents are people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Doctors and AIDS-serving NGOs call such views anti-medical and see their spread as a serious threat.
