"In Libya, we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict"
The Russian authorities have recently intensified their policy in the Libyan direction, and visits to Moscow have been attended by delegations of the rival Libyan parties.
The head of the Russian contact group for the intra-Libyan settlement under the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma, the assistant of the head of the Chechen Republic Lev Denegov told "Ъ", what goals Moscow pursues in this region and who it bets on.
The contact group you're leading on Libya is virtually unknown.
Let's say the contact group on Ukraine -- everybody knows about it.
And here is the veil of mystery.
What exactly do you do, what are your goals?
The contact group was created on the initiative of the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma.
Its activities are supervised by Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (Duma deputy from Chechnya - "Ъ").
The latter is authorized to work on the Libyan direction by the Speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The group was formed after the arrest of the Russian tanker "Mehanik Chebotarev" in Libya (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board).
We've been thinking about how we can help the crew.
Then a contact group was formed from military specialists, representatives of the State Duma, and our work was supported by the head of Chechnya, Ramzan Kadyrov.
How come you're the one who's running it?
Since I've been working on Libya since 2008, I've been asked to lead the team.
Our activities were not limited to the release of the sailors from the Mechanic Chebotarev.
We have been able to establish contacts with representatives of all the major factions that are opposed to each other in the Libyan conflict - both from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government led by Faiz Saraj is based) and Tobruk (the residence of the parliament that opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern regions of Libya).
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Vice Prime Minister of Libya - "Ъ"), we managed to quickly negotiate the release of the Russian sailors.
So it was decided to use these contacts more effectively, to create a contact group.
Its task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I want to emphasize that in Libya we do not want to associate ourselves with any of the parties to the conflict, we are in dialogue with all of them.
How many people are in the contact group and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
There are five people in the contact group now.
Among them are people with experience in law enforcement, including the Defense Ministry.
We also want to bring in a group of experts from the region, representatives of the RAS Middle East Institute.
None of our staff are in Libya at all, so there's no need for that.
Are there any Russian military advisers, instructors in Libya right now?
And if so, whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All the talk and all the publicity about it is not true.
But your contact group includes ex-military...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
Like when we visit hot spots.
Or closed cities like Misurata, which is home to militia units that played a role in the 2011 overthrow of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi and have intensified in the years since.
We arrived in Misrata in January of this year.
We were scared, told that they were all Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation ourselves, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why there are rumors, what is the role of Islamists in the situation.
In Misurata, we met with all the representatives of the detachments that were engaged in the destruction of ISIS in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was taken from the militants of the banned "Islamic State" - "Ъ").
We wanted to look at them, meet these people, verify the information that they were the ones who played a crucial role in the destruction of ISIS in Libya, not Khalifa Haftar, who was taking credit for it.
And what did you come up with?
Haftar didn't win the fight against ISIS in Libya?
He didn't do that.
Haftar was operating on the other front, in Benghazi.
And ISIS in Sirte was fought by the government-controlled structures in Tripoli.
And by the way, we invited the people who were running this counterterrorism operation to Russia.
And they came - the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April this year, the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, in the Duma, the Foreign Ministry and the Russian Guard.
We understand that you've been to all the regions of Libya, and you probably have a sense of the mood of the local elites and field commanders.
Do you think that the ceasefire and election agreements reached in Paris at the end of July by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj will be implemented?
Or again, as has happened many times in the past, will the agreements be broken, fighting will resume, and the parties will try to seize power alone?
It's a good sign that Saraj and Haftar have agreed to meet again, which was impossible not so long ago.
In the recent past, both leaders have had extremely negative comments about each other.
As for Russia's position...
It is often written and said that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe it.
We encountered this situation when we were in Misrata, and Haftar was boarding the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov on that very day.
It was a coincidence.
But in Misrata, they didn't believe in coincidence.
They said, "You must be very brave people to come to us today".
But our task is to show that we are not just supporting Haftar, we are engaging with all the key players in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar have been in touch.
Does the fact that he studied twice in the USSR make it easier to understand Russian partners on a human, emotional level?
And by the way, does Haftar speak Russian?
Russian, if he knows, is very relative.
But what he learned from us, of course, makes it easier to talk to him.
And not just him, by the way.
When we talk to the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who have either studied in Russia or the Soviet Union.
And they speak Russian perfectly.
And they're drawn to Russia, they're somewhat nostalgic about it.
Do you think it's possible to lift the arms embargo on Libya soon?
Are your Libyan counterparts interested in Russian arms supplies?
Interested, of course, but as I said, we are not on the side of any party in this conflict and we would not like to arm one against the other.
We'd like everyone to be in roughly equal positions.
As for the arms embargo, there are constant calls from the Libyans for Russia to help lift it.
The process of drafting a constitution is currently underway in Libya.
We hope the parties will reach a compromise, reach an internal consensus.
Then there should be elections, which was also discussed at the meeting between Saraj and Haftar.
If elections are held and a legitimate government is finally elected (and neither party has that status now), then the question of lifting the arms embargo can be raised at the UN Security Council.
Raising this issue now is pointless and dangerous, it will only escalate the conflict.
The other day, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees swimming from Libya, felt abandoned by its EU allies.
Can Moscow help its Italian partners in this situation by using its ties with the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is it that Haftar's troops will take control of the coast and end the smuggling business that is smuggling immigrants to Europe?
That's a very timely question.
We're working hard on that.
The Italians need Russia's support because Moscow is in dialogue with Haftar, Saraj, Misurata and the south of the country.
And the tribes in southern Libya have a big role to play in this, and they're willing to cooperate with Russia.
Is this about the southerners stopping the migration flows at long range?
So, you mean, they turned back the buses that were carrying Nigerian migrants?
That's what we're trying to do.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in keeping these flows going.
We hope to help unite the southerners in the negotiation process between the Saraj, Haftar and the tribes in the south.
But first, we'd like to see a consensus on this issue between Haftar and Saraj.
Prime Minister Faiz Saraj is considered an Islamist, and supporter of the introduction of Sharia law in the country.
How radical is his views?
Would it be an obstacle to building relations with Russia or the West?
I'll give you my personal opinion of him.
In my opinion, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But the Islamists are in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself is of the opinion that Libya should be a perfectly normal country - moderately Islamic, open to the world.
And he's also actively fighting terrorists.
What is his reputation?
It was created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, the seat of the legislative, executive and judicial branches.
There's the national oil corporation, the national bank and other governmental structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in keeping us out of it.
We mixed up all the cards and started to actively communicate with both Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we're already reaping the fruits of that work: Rosneft has signed a cooperation agreement with the Libyan state oil company, NOC.
The director of NOC, Mustafa Sanalla, with whom Rosneft's head, Igor Sechin, made the deal, is himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil from Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with her?
I think I'm going to resell it.
What other economic interests does Russia have in Libya?
Plans to re-sign contracts signed under Muammar Gaddafi.
The agreement is based on previous agreements in the transport sector (construction of railways), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
Do the Libyans have anything to pay?
Well, they have oil.
So, like in the case of Iran, this is an oil-for-services scheme?
I don't know what the pattern is, these are not the issues I'm dealing with directly.
The economy is not really the main thing for Russia in Libya.
We're basically doing peacekeeping work there.
What's important to us is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans come to terms with each other so that they can establish order in their own country and Libya ceases to be a conducive environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, that is the main task - to help the Libyan people and to drive the terrorists out of Libya.
Do you have any information about the presence in Libya (now or formerly) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee who said that there are no Russians or other former Soviet countries in Libya today.
He said he had about 50,000 phone records of Islamic and radical groups (in Libya. - "Ъ") and Russian language was not heard there.
What country are these militants from?
I wouldn't want to go into that detail.
Then we'll put it another way.
How many of the Islamist militants in Libya are Libyans themselves?
Libyans are barely even in the top five.
The rest are just a bunch of pricks.
Can Moscow conduct intra-Libyan negotiations on the model of Paris?
There are plans.
We are actively negotiating with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have declared their readiness to come again - to Moscow or Grozny.
When can such talks be held?
It's hard to say now.
There are still a few more visits to be made, and then I hope we can get some clarity on when and where to hold the talks.
