Michelle Carter sentenced for messages that led to the suicide of Conrad Roy
A Massachusetts woman was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for encouraging her boyfriend, Conrad Roy, to commit suicide by texting and calling.
Michelle Carter, now 20, will serve 15 months of her sentence and five years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father said at the hearing on Thursday: "My family is devastated.
My son was my best friend".
Carter was allowed to remain free until an appeal.
She was facing a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red pants and a cream blouse, was standing, holding hands and eyes closed.
"Her actions killed Conrad Roy", the prosecutor told the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve her own.
She didn't take responsibility", she said.
"She showed no remorse".
But Carter's lawyer said it was "a tragic incident that she deeply regrets".
However, Justice Lawrence Moniz said that in his opinion, her "age, level of maturity or even mental illness did not significantly affect her actions".
The prosecutor read Roy's mother, Lynn Roy, a statement that said: "Not a day has passed that I have not mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and how I'm coping - I'm trying to support his sisters despite all the pain that will stay with us forever", it says.
Roy's sister Camden Roy said she was haunted by the thought that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become the aunt of his children.
"Losing someone who has been with me since I was born is a pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life", she said.
This case is likely to set a legal precedent, since there is no law in Massachusetts that holds a person liable for advising someone to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in his car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17.
The case attracted national attention when it was revealed that he was driven to suicide by a Carter message.
"You can hang yourself, jump off a roof, stab yourself, I don't know, there are many ways", she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was on vacation with his family.
Minutes before she killed herself, she wrote, "You must do this, Conrad", and "You just have to turn on the light, and you will be free and happy".
Judge Monis said Carter wanted to get attention with Roy's death, and he forbade her to talk to the press to keep her from getting what she wanted.
Lawyers are divided on this.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of murdering her British roommate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
