The dinosaur used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, though it is terrifying.
The researchers said that the first remains of an incredible creature the size of a rhinoceros, discovered by a Canadian miner, were so well preserved that experts called it the "Mona Lisa of dinosaurs".
It was so well preserved that they were even able to determine that the color of his scaly skin was reddish-brown and say that he had, in a way, a dark past.
A report published in the journal Modern Biology described it as "the best preserved Tireophore in the history of discovery and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world".
This is a fossil -- a recently discovered specimen of a nodosaur that lived in the middle Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
Its incredibly good condition has stunned researchers, who call it "really remarkable".
This herbivorous thyreophore is the best-preserved fossil of its kind in the history of discovery, according to an article in National Geographic magazine.
It was found by Sean Fank while working at the Sancor Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He stumbled upon something that seemed to be different from the surrounding breed, and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil he found was sent to the Royal Paleontological Museum of Tirrell.
For the next six years, work was underway to find an animal inside a mass of 2,500 feet (1100 kilograms).
Now that all this hard work is done, the finished product can be demonstrated.
"It's only a little bit of a pinch, and you can almost believe it's asleep", says lead author Caleb Brown, a research associate at the Royal Tirrell Paleontological Museum, where the creature is on display.
It will go down in science history as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaur specimens.
By studying its skin, researchers found that it was a herbivore, and although it was covered in armor and resembled a walking tank, it was apparently in considerable danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This powerful armor-covered dinosaur used red-and-white camouflage to hide from predators, and it employed a defensive technique known as defensive dyeing, which is also used by many animals today.
This would allow it to blend in more quickly and avoid encounters with enemies, experts say, suggesting that larger dinosaurs were hunting it.
This 110-million-year-old creature from the family of nodosaurs was widely covered in the press in May, and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
Scientists have already studied the animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of museum lab technician Mark Mitchell, one of the team members who spent more than 7,000 hours digging it out.
The remarkable preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the scales and plates on his body.
They found a protective dye, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, which means the top of the creature was darker than its underside.
Although protective dye is well-established, the discovery came as a surprise because the size of the Borealopelta is far larger than that of any animal with protective dye currently in existence.
It's possible that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution preferred the disguise of confrontation as a way of survival.
But most of the modern protective-colored animals - such as deer, zebras, or armored cats - are much smaller and more accessible prey, suggesting that the nodosaur had to fight hard to survive.
"The serious predator threat to the massive, powerful armor-covered dinosaur shows just how dangerous the predatory dinosaurs of the Cretaceous period were", Brown said.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds in the dinosaur's scales also suggests that its skin must have been reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, looking for information about its life, including the preserved contents of its digestive tract, to find out what it ate during its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into the river and was swept into the sea, where it sank and lay back down on the ocean floor.
Alberta was as warm as southern Florida is today, and the rivers and oceans likely extended farther inland than they do now.
"This nodosaur is really remarkable in that it's completely covered in preserved scaly skin, and at the same time it's completely preserved in three dimensions, preserving the original animal form", Brown said.
As a result, the animal now looks almost exactly as it did in the Early Cretaceous.
You don't have to use your imagination to recreate it, you just have to look at it a little bit, and you can almost believe it's asleep.
The Cretaceous is the time when giant theropods, two-legged carnivorous dinosaurs, roamed the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of them, Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, the tyrreophorus could have been hunted by one of its formidable ancestors.
They include the acrocanthosaurus, a monster that is 38 feet (11.5 meters) long and weighs six tons.
Scientists whose latest findings are published in the journal Modern Biology believe that Borealopelta was taken to the sea after death and mummified in the seaweed.
