According to the museum, it is the best preserved thyreophore in the world, along with the skin and armor, and it is intact from the snout to the femur.
On average, these creatures reached about 18 feet (five meters) in length and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1300 kilograms).
Their distinctive feature was two twenty-inch spines protruding from the shoulders.
Researchers believe that this herbivorous tyreophore struggled to find its way across what is now Canada until a flooded river washed it into the open sea.
But the dinosaur's underwater burial preserved its shell with precision down to the smallest detail.
The fossil remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remains of the skin still cover the furry armor plates along the dinosaur's skull.
As Michael Gresko wrote in an article for National Geographic magazine, the degree of preservation is "seldom as much as winning the lottery".
The longer I look at it, the more amazing it seems.
Fossil remains of the skin still cover the scaly plates that line the animal's skull.
His right front leg is extended along the side, with five toes on it bent upward.
