The origin of the resemblance: artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of the hall in the Friedman Gallery in New York, there's a ceiling wire hanging people's faces -- white, black, brown -- all in some subtle way similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Harborg from cheekprints and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent me clippings from Fort Leavenworth, where a former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for the infamous transfer of confidential diplomatic cables on the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which opened August 2, is called "The Origin of Similarity".
This is the result of two years of correspondence between Dewey Harburg, whose art blends technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender woman and a famous dissident whose sentence was commuted by Barack Obama just three days before his presidency ended.
By analyzing the DNA obtained from Manning's computer program and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of the individuals who might have had such a genome, Dewey Harburg created a profound, though difficult to grasp, manifesto, not only about the plasticity of DNA data - the various ways of interpreting it and the inherent determinism of those interpretations - but also about the notion of identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has openly identified herself as a woman since she was a teenager, was convicted in 2013 of 20 counts, including six counts of violating the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her photos in prison were not available, so only one photograph of her was known: a grainy black-and-white selfie of Manning in a platinum wig, clearly feeling embarrassed, behind the wheel of a car; this is the photo she became associated with.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborgh successfully completed her 2012 project "Visions of Strangers".
In it, she created portraits of unknown people using forensic evidence like pickles and gum, extracting DNA from the rubbish and creating images of what those people might look like.
And then she got an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some portrait to illustrate the article", Dewey-Hagborg explained at a preview of the new exhibition for the press.
Chelsea wasn't allowed to visit and be photographed at the time, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted a portrait made from her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her imprisoned muse became correspondence friends and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote a comic book, "Repressed Images", illustrated by Sholey Cango, which depicted how the future president would mitigate Chelsea's punishment and allow her to visit the exhibition in person.
That Obama actually decided to release Manning just days after the book was published was a pleasant surprise after seven grueling years in a military prison in Kansas.
There's something profound and powerful about the fact that the exhibition opens right now, when Donald Trump is declaring war on government whistleblowers, and inventing new ways to fuel the hostility on Twitter that he's designed to mitigate.
When Dewey Harburg was asked about the coincidence of all this in time, she said that "nothing happens by chance".
In a statement written on the gallery wall, Manning's huge signature at the bottom (with a heart instead of a dot above the "i" in her last name) calls for an end to "automatic segregation based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture".
On the opposite side is her mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar made of C, G, and A pencils.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist so elegantly puts it scientifically), Dewey-Harborg hoped to show how remarkably similar we all are, at least in our biological structure.
"I hope to explain to people that our genome doesn't define what we are, how open the genetic data is to interpretation and how subjective it is", said Dewey-Harborg, whose 2007 video work "False Memories" is also on display here.
"DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of those stories are here".
The last piece of the exhibition, which fits in one room, is the comic book novel mentioned above.
It shows Manning in a King Kong style over the U.S. Correctional Facility building with a loudspeaker in his hand.
"If they kill your speech, they win", it says.
"So never shut up".
"This is a direct quote from a letter she wrote me", says the artist who greets us from Philadelphia.
"I still get wrinkles when I say it".
Manning hasn't seen the exhibit in person yet -- as it was prophetically portrayed in the comics -- but when she does, she'll be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genomic simulacrum, gathered like a crowd of protesters.
This is also done on purpose, as is everything in the exhibition up to the height of 5'2, Manning's height, where the genetic haplogroups were drawn with pencil.
"I used to hang them on the walls, but now I wanted them to look like a crowd", says Dewey Harburg of the portraits.
"I wanted them to be like the mass movement that formed around Chelsea, as a movement that stood for her liberation".
