Startups that will help your company not become another Uber
Aimee Hermette wanted to measure employee satisfaction at her e-commerce startup, but the polls didn't work.
The answers were often vague, useless, or worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some of the staff didn't trust the process.
"He was never consistent or objective", said Errett, who runs Madison Reed, a 75-person e-commerce hair care company in San Francisco.
So she turned to third parties for help.
Now, a new kind of human resources startup is emerging that helps companies find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software that measures employee engagement, they enable companies to do quick surveys, target specific teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and a hotline for complaints, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass top management and contact management directly.
"Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, where is Fitbit for your company?" says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Redwood City startup Glynt, whose analytics software is used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she gained a greater understanding of what her employees think and feel over the three years she spent using Glint.
In addition to express surveys and questionnaires of specific teams, the product offers a heat map of the company and shows in visual form which departments have more complaints and which managers have low approval ratings, allowing it to understand why.
Companies are beginning to realize that they need to control the workplace or they will become another Uber that got caught up in the scandal when a former employee posted a blog post describing an aggressive environment in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For startups like Glint, this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for profitable business.
The financial technology portal Let's Talk About Payments estimates that the global governance, regulation and compliance industry could be worth more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
Denver, Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, saw a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid a downturn in Uber's reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber has become a popular choice.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customized staff opinion polls, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides an anonymous text message hotline that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the top manager is involved, the complaints go straight to the board.
"The court of public opinion has seized power from the inspectors", said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If a company is found to be mismanaging or behaving unethically, even if inspectors do not intervene, the company could face costly consequences in the form of customer boycotts, employee outflows and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with over 25,000 employees in 500 locations, has been using Convercent for over a year to make sure employees are aware of the rules and procedures and to offer a simple way to contact the company's headquarters.
In the past, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she would have to look up a phone number or an email address at the head office, file a formal complaint, and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a scary and awkward experience, said James Vitrano, chief legal officer of Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now, when a company uses Convercent, problems that were previously hidden from managers in offices in other cities or states - such as discrimination, harassment, and unfair pay - can be detected and addressed more quickly.
"I can get closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the situation of employees", said Vitrano, who heads the Ruby Tuesday network risk management team.
And we protect our shareholders from employee lawsuits.
According to Quinland, companies began to take ethics, values and employee engagement more seriously in 2002, after Arthur Andersen's accounting firm collapsed due to ethical violations as a result of the Enron Affair.
But it wasn't until social media became widespread that companies realized they couldn't keep their dirty laundry from spreading online.
"Before technology was used to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy", he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies regular fees for using their products.
It's a business model and an opportunity that has been embraced by venture capitalists who have backed both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company's total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research shows that employees today expect more from their jobs than ever before.
In highly competitive markets like Silicon Valley, high wages and exciting projects are just the bare minimum.
Employees want to feel accepted and appreciated, and that they are giving their time to a company with a positive mission.
"When people are happy working at a company, when they feel heard, and when they feel that the work they do is productive, they are more likely to make the company successful", says Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors get a return when their portfolio companies do well; companies do well when their employees are committed and engaged.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it's no surprise that they're finding support.
Workplace culture experts say it's important to have data on employee engagement.
But the data is useless until the trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can create the impression that change is coming.
And if change doesn't happen fast enough, or doesn't happen at all, it can lead to frustration and employees losing interest.
"If you're going to ask for 4,000 suggestions, you should be prepared to have 4,000 conversations", says Russell Rutt, president of consulting at management firm Kotter International, who has seen companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
Because if you don't go all the way, the staff will think, "Did you really hear me?"
You don't care about that?
If you don't care, why shouldn't I?
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action the same day someone reports a problem using Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from employees who were unhappy with the speed of decision making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve the problems.
Ruby Tuesday is learning more about its employees and hopes that in the long run, this knowledge will help it retain employees more effectively in an industry known for high turnover.
"If you don't try to create a culture of transparency, you're going to lose people", Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose the company.
