To create a comic novel: One castle in English history
In the recent past, the tiny Scottney Castle was featured in the music video "Squeeze", and in the '70s and '80s, it served as a safe haven for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy home in the Beule River valley in Kent, he's been watching the tumultuous history around him, and now he's inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshire man with a bearded hair and a penchant for historical documents, to write a comic novel.
"I find it so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago", he says enthusiastically.
"You feel it so personal when you hold that letter in your hand".
"A Castle in England" covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and tells of the families who lived in Scotney; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Bryony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first book to be based on archival data: in 2014 he wrote Dead Man's Teeth and Other Stories, a collection of British Library documents, a project that unexpectedly touched him deeply.
"I could be torn apart by a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700's by a double agent working for the Jacobites", he says.
"This is his fingerprint".
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those days, they used to light a fire.
And 300 years from now, in the future, you feel like you're there too.
Oh, how I love the archives!"
For someone so obsessed with old paper, getting a grant from the National Endowment for the Arts and the Arts Council of England and living in a castle for four months ("I've been staying there a little bit, to be honest") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent days studying the "new" Victorian castle, going through the archives and examining the estate's many treasures and antiquities - such as the heads of hyenas on the walls or bottles that had been lying in a ditch for centuries.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to foresters, gardeners and sometimes the artists who worked on the illustrations for his book.
Then at night he "drunk whiskey and sat down to write".
The history of Scotney Castle is not well-studied, because the National Trust only gained full access to it in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hassey, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff had only begun to dig into the archive, which he describes as "something aristocrats have been dumping in the attic for centuries".
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You might think land disputes are boring", says Rhodes, "but here's a birch that two families fought over.
It happens, you guys!"
In some stories in the collection, the castle becomes a starting point for broader searches into English history: for example, in The Workman, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
"There is a record of a rebellion that took place in the castle in 1380, in a book called The Knights of Kent and Sussex", says Rhodes.
"The peasant uprising started in these places, and I thought that the uprising was a good start.
Maybe they were connected?"
Other plots are strongly connected with the castle's history - for example, "The Priest", which tells of a Jesuit priest whom the Darrel family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "The Smuggler", about 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have faked his own funeral by stuffing his coffin with stones (this was discovered years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Darrells are the Rhodes family's favorite of all Scotney residents: "The gentlemen seem to have been complete swindlers, always in debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, the Darrell men have solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy older women - I imagine them as a company of handsome young men who know how to look after the heirs of great fortunes".
After completing his work at Rhodes Castle, he looks for other opportunities to gain unique writing experience.
He spent two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elamyanmäki - a place where in the early 20th century there was a sanatorium, and then it was again covered with forest.
But Scotny is still a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave", he says.
"I was like, 'Oh, shit, I need to get back to real life again.'
