Andrei Okhlopkov was transferred from the spaceport
As it became known to "Ъ", the technical director of the East cosmodrome Andrey Ochlopkov started working at the State Space Scientific-Productive Center (GKNPC) named after Hruchnitchev.
Previously, he de facto engaged in the construction of the East spaceport, but due to disagreements with the management of the Center for the exploitation of terrestrial and space infrastructure (CENKI) was transferred to the enterprise in Moscow Filhas, where he will coordinate production.
Mr. Ochlopkov will not have a shiftman: the post of technical director will most likely be abolished, and the functional will be dispersed among the units of the Central Election Commission.
The technical director of the Eastern and the deputy director general of the Central Scientific and Technological Institute for Technological Development, Andrey Ochlopkov, has moved to work at the Khruchnitchev-named State-owned Nuclear Power Plant, top managers of several space industry enterprises, as well as a government official, told "Ъ".
"He has been working on the new post for several weeks", the industry source told Kommersant.
The Central Intelligence Agency failed to get an operational comment on Thursday, and Mr. Ochlopkov himself was unavailable for comment.
However, the information "Ъ" officially confirmed in the GKNPC.
He decided to move to the position of director for production coordination, - said the company. - Andrei Ochlopkov fully fulfilled the task set before him to ensure the launch minimum for the first launch at the Vostokny spaceport.
Mr. Ochlopkov joined the Central Intelligence Agency in 2013, having served in the space forces, in particular at Baikonur, and in Plesetsk - at the "northern" spaceport, holding the post of first deputy commander in the rank of colonel.
In 2009, Andrey Ochlopkov became a defendant in a criminal case.
The investigation accused him of bribery: allegedly from his submission, regional commercialists received state orders for refusal, but did not fulfill their obligations to clean up the separated parts of the launchers in the Arkhangelsk region and the Komi Republic.
In 2012, a jury found him not guilty.
The tasks assigned to him in the CENKI for technological development were extended to different projects, but the main one was the construction of a spaceport in the Far East.
Oleg Ostapenko, then head of the Federal Space Agency, said in an interview with "Kommersant" that the situation in the Eastern "was critical already in October 2013".
The fact is that a strategic mistake was made in the planning: the completion of the construction and the first launch of the Soyuz-2.1 launch vehicle were planned for the same time - the end of 2015.
To complete the start-up before the end of the year, the construction was decided to be completed six months earlier and the deadlines were moved from December to July 2015.
To speed up the process, the experts of the Central Electrotechnical Institute began to carry out parallel installation of technological equipment on unbuilt objects.
The main proponent of this idea was Andrei Ochlopkov.
Despite the risks and the postponement (instead of December 2015, the Soyuz flew on April 28, 2016), the idea proved to be a good idea, says a source at the spaceport: "Otherwise we would not have made a single launch from the Eastern, but would have been building".
Vice-Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin, who oversaw the creation of the spaceport, jokingly called Andrei Ochlopkov his "cosmic Susanin", but it was almost always him who requested information about the progress of construction.
Mr. Ochlopkov also remembered the directness: for example, in an interview with "Kommersant" he proposed to deprive the Federal Agency for Special Construction (Spekström) of the status of the only contractor in the Eastern Region and to work directly with subcontractors: "Why should we put all the eggs in one basket of Spekström?"
This idea has found support in the government.
Since 2017, CENKI has taken on the duties of the general contractor to complete the construction and installation work on the start-up and technical complex by the scheduled fourth quarter of the start-up.
According to "Ъ", the reason for Mr. Ochlopkov's transfer to the new place of work was disagreements with the management of the CENKI regarding the methods of completing the construction of the structures and complexes of the spaceport, as well as the methods of working with subcontracting organizations.
"It was decided that this would be best for everyone", says one of the top managers involved in building the Oriental.
A government official, for his part, called the decision strange: "He was one of the best specialists, and it will be difficult to find an equivalent replacement".
According to "Ъ", this will not be necessary: the position of technical director of the spaceport will be abolished, and its functions will be spread across the subdivisions of the CENKI.
