Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help ease the effects of HDL.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive system.
But recent research suggests otherwise: A diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products may help alleviate symptoms in those with inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable disease, which affects an estimated 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, causes colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Usually, people are advised to avoid meat and dairy products to alleviate symptoms, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid in protein, tryptophan, helps to produce immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Leading researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells in the gut keep harmful microbes from entering the body when they come from food.
The cells that trigger the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body while not harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too much disturbed in the inflammatory direction, it can lead to inflammatory bowel disease.
The experiments showed that mice that had a certain bacterium in their intestines had a cell tolerance booster.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan, one of the building blocks of the protein, to trigger the cell formation.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between a species of bacteria, Lactobacillus reuteri, which is part of the normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan in the mice's diet, the more of these immune cells they had".
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could promote a more tolerant and less inflammatory environment in the intestine.
Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barraganvas, a postdoc, studying a variety of immune cells that increase tolerance, found that one group of test mice had these cells, and another group, which belonged to the same line but was kept separate, did not.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the gut microbiome of mice - communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
So we sequenced the DNA of the intestinal cells of the mice, and we found six types of bacteria that were present in the mice that had immune cells, but not in the mice that didn't have them.
Mice raised in sterile environments, which didn't have a good microbiome and didn't develop this type of immune cell, got L. reuteri, and they had immune cells.
To understand how the bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid medium and then transferred small portions of the liquid - without the bacteria - to underdeveloped immune cells secreted from mice.
The immune cells have turned into tolerance-boosting cells.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of the processing of tryptophan, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells also fell by about 50 percent.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same cell tolerance-enhancing genes as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan byproducts from L. reuteri promote cell development in humans as they do in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
She says, "Perhaps we need to increase the development of these cells, because they are the ones that are responsible for the inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestine.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri could potentially lead to an expansion of their population".
