The White House prop cost the taxpayers thousands of dollars.
According to military records provided to TIME magazine, the White House's decision last month to fly a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American manufacturing cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as the Marine One when the president is on board, was the centerpiece of a July 17 event at the White House that showcased American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials examined technology products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut-made helicopter was displayed alongside a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a truck from Mississippi.
According to records of the Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the unit responsible for helicopter control, the White House War Department ordered the helicopter's presence in a private order, or FRAGO, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn for an unusual event.
"I just wanted to make sure you were aware because this is an unusual, widely reported event", the commander of HMX-1 wrote in an e-mail to his superior, the first deputy chief of aviation of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter stated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on July 17 for an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and would remain there until the lawn was cleared between 6 and 9 p.m. that same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be needed for the return flight in accordance with the restrictions on hours of operation.
The first crew escorted the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security personnel remained near the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the recordings obtained by TIME magazine, it remains unclear whether a second crew was eventually needed.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 has clarified whether the event is in violation of this order.
"We asked among other things if this was a violation of Hatch's law, and we were told no", the commander wrote.
"Looks like you have nowhere to go", the deputy chief replied.
The event was declared an official event by the White House, and was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
During the event, the president made efforts to advance the health care reform that was in the Senate's pipeline at the time, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of airships known as Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But asking them for the sole purpose of being able to photograph is unusual.
Trump already became a subject of discussion in February when the presidential plane flew in the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
"The White House is thrilled with the Made in America show, which showcased products from all 50 states made by American workers using American materials", said White House deputy press secretary Lindsey Walters.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington metropolitan area and the South Lawn to train transporting the President of the United States to the White House with accuracy down to an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, the HMX-1 made 58 training landings outside the White House.
According to one official, the flight performed for the Made in America event was counted as a necessary training flight for the crew for a month.
The unit's helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of the "non-presidential support mission".
According to the White House, the taxpayers did not pay for any of the other exhibits on display.
A representative of the company Sikorsky reported that the company did not participate in the organization of the demonstration of the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep track of the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Department of Defense's hourly rates for fiscal year 2017, the Department of Defense's rate of compensation for a VH-3D is $24,380 per hour of flight.
The unit records show that the time the aircraft spent in the air was 30 minutes each way from its airfield at Marine Corps Air Base Quantico in Virginia.
The White House claims the real cost of using a helicopter is far below that rate.
"It is completely wrong to calculate the cost to taxpayers on the basis of an estimated rate of compensation", says Walters.
These approximate rates include staff, maintenance and many other non-refundable costs that are included in the annual appropriations.
According to a 2015 RAND study, the compensation rates do not include the cost of personnel, but do take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and contract expenses.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer spoke out in defense of using a helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to showcase things that are made in America this week", Spicer said.
And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to national security, and that there are, I'm guessing, hundreds if not thousands of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think like most Americans, we're all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans worked tirelessly to create.
So, of course, it's perfectly appropriate to pay attention to this.
It was unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter while surveying the South Lawn during the event, but he was definitely in the driver's seat of the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed representatives of the company Sikorsky, joking with the press about his own fleet of products from the company.
"I know Sikorsky well", said the President. "I have three of them".
