Paris Saint-Germain will not stop pursuing Neymar after the club offered £189 million for his ransom, but did they warn Barcelona of the world record-setting attack three years ago?
The sensational offer revived the summer transfer window, when the Ligue 1 club were poised to break a world record for transfer fees, more than doubling the previous mark linked to Paul Pogba's return to Manchester United last season for £89 million.
When the transfer is complete, Neymar will become the world's most expensive player, as well as the highest paid professional athlete in the world, as PSG offers him a salary of over £500,000 a week in net terms.
Barcelona are known to be furious about the way the offer was made and how Neymar broke the contract, despite the fact that, as a source close to the Catalan club's management insists, the club has always done everything possible for the player since his move from Santos in 2013.
But wasn't the football world warned of this possibility three years ago by President Bush?
When Manchester City expressed interest in signing Blaze Matuiidi in 2014, Nasser Al-Khelaify issued a stern warning to any club that wanted to lure one of PSG's best players.
"I don't worry because they know that if they touch one of our players, then we will go against them, we will make offers to their players", Al-Helaifi said.
We respect all clubs.
But if they try to recruit one of our players, there will be consequences.
Barcelona seem to have crossed that line when the Spanish club expressed interest in PSG midfielder Marco Verratti earlier this summer.
PSG have made it clear that they will not release the Italian player under any circumstances, and now Barcelona are probably feeling the consequences of their offer in the form of losing one of their most valuable players, Neymar.
